    <text>
        <body>
            <head>12. Memorandum From the Undersecretary of Defense for Policy (<persName
                    corresp="recs2P7y12AuR9gIG">Ikle</persName>) to Secretary of Defense <persName
                    corresp="recg0WDsRQgtuIKMw">Weinberge</persName>r<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d12fn1">Source: <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma"
                        >National Security Council</orgName>, National Security Council
                    Institutional Files, Box SR—101, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"><orgName
                            corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName></gloss> 00049, <gloss
                        target="#t_RWR_1">RWR</gloss> 5/03/82 <gloss target="#t_START_1"
                        >START</gloss>. Secret.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1982-05-03"
                        >May 3, 1982</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">False Arguments Against <gloss target="#t_OSD_1"
                        ><orgName corresp="recoMngX7uLPacWDx">OSD</orgName></gloss> Approach</p>
            <p rendition="simple_italic">1. Slippage in Negotiation.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Argument:</hi> Soviets are unlikely to accept 2
                million kg <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> limit; if
                a compromise is reached at, say 3.5 million, <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >US</placeName> won’t be able to reach Soviet <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                    type="topic">throw-weight</rs>.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Answer:</hi> Slippage might be even more likely with
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic"><orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl"
                        >State</orgName>’s</hi> approach: Soviets may not accept all the collateral
                constraints and insist on higher launcher number, as a result of which Soviet
                throw-weights could far exceed ours.</p>
            <p rendition="simple_italic">2. “Unverifiability” of <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                    type="topic">Throw-weight</rs>.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Argument:</hi> There is a 20% uncertainty of <rs
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs>
                <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>, which could cover
                the entire <rs corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky" type="topic">SS-18</rs> force.</p>
            <pb facs="0069" n="40" xml:id="pg_40"/>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Answer:</hi> The uncertainty level in <rs
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> might be even more
                pronounced with State’s indirect approach if the complicated collateral constraints
                don’t quite work as supposed to.</p>
            <p>Also, <gloss target="#t_OSD_1"><orgName corresp="recoMngX7uLPacWDx"
                    >OSD</orgName></gloss> not opposed to a collateral <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> constraint limiting
                launchers.</p>
            <p rendition="simple_italic">3. <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic"
                    >Throw-weight</rs> Better Approached Indirectly.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Argument:</hi> Direct approach offends Soviets, or is
                not comprehensible to public.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Answer:</hi> Soviets fully understand <rs
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> and have recently
                indicated they expect us to propose <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic"
                    >throw-weight</rs> limits. Also, there has been a great deal of <orgName
                    corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congressional</orgName> and expert debate, so that
                public will readily receive a clear explanation on the basis of the media
                reaction.</p>
            <p>To aim <hi rendition="simple_italic">indirectly</hi> at <rs
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> restrictions will be
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">more</hi> confusing to public; it will lack
                simplicity because of all the collateral constraints about “new types” of missiles
                that are prohibited, etc., and will seem rather disingenuous. (Are the Soviets
                supposed not to notice that they are being asked “indirectly” to cut back sharply on
                    <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs>?)</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold"><persName corresp="recs2P7y12AuR9gIG">Fred C.
                            Ikle</persName></hi>
                    <note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d12fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this
                        typed signature.</note>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
